Title : Rose Beaudet
Text : [[Image:Rose Beaudet NYPL.jpg|thumb|right|Rose Beaudet in about 1890]]

'''Rose Beaudet''' (1862&ndash;1947) was an American actress and opera singer of the late [[Victorian era]] and early 20th century who regularly appeared in [[musical theatre]].

She was born as Eliza Lang, the daughter of Councilman Lewis H. Lang (1836-1912) of [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] near [[San Francisco]], and his wife Mary Ann Lang (1848 -1878). She married S. Arlant Edwards on 15 January 1891,<ref>[http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/digital/collections/cul/texts/ldpd_5655288_004/pages/ldpd_5655288_004_00000012.html?toggle=&menu=maximize&top=&left= ''The New York Clipper Annual'' -New York :  Frank Queen Pub. Co.,  1883- (1892)]</ref> but had divorced him by 1902. She appeared with the C. D. Willard Company in 1903.<ref>[http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SFC19020427.2.122 'Stockton Actress Signs With Willard Company' - San Francisco Call, Volume 87, Number 148, 27 April 1902]</ref>

A [[mezzo-soprano]], Beaudet's appearances on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] included Eva in ''[[Der Bettelstudent|The Beggar Student]]'' at the [[Casino Theatre (New York City)|Casino Theatre]] (1883 - 1884), ''Amorita'' at the Casino Theatre (1885), Captain Delauney in ''[[Erminie]]'' at the Casino Theatre (1886), a role played in the original London production by [[Kate Everleigh]], '' The Kitchen Belle'' (1889), Mrs St Mirim in  ''Miss Innocence Abroad'' at the [[Bijou Theatre (Manhattan)|Bijou Theatre]] (1894), Catherine in ''[[Lost, Strayed or Stolen]]''  at the [[Fifth Avenue Theatre]] (1896), ''All on Account of Eliza'' at the [[Garrick Theatre (New York City)|Garrick Theatre]] and [[Wallack's Theatre]] (1900 - 1901), ''The Cardinal'' at the [[Garden Theatre]] (1902), Mrs Jefferson Briscoe in  ''[[The County Chairman (play)|The County Chairman]]''  at Wallack's Theatre (1903 - 1904), Marcie Brook in ''Miss Jack''  at the [[Herald Square Theatre]] (1911), and Mrs Kennion in ''The Younger Generation'' and in ''Half an Hour''  at the [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]] (1913).<ref>[http://ibdb.com/person.php?id=66851 Beaudet on the [[Internet Broadway Database]]]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OVdShkzkX74C&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=rose+beaudet+stage&source=bl&ots=tsw4072nmf&sig=IrIwsoefDlnK3UaBWN8Sd3UozYk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cD1hU-jaBsPB7AbgpIHQCA&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=rose%20beaudet%20stage&f=false Bordman, Gerald Martin, ''American Musical Theatre: A Chronicle'' - [[Oxford University Press]] (2010)]</ref>

She died in 1947 and is buried in Stockton Rural Cemetery with her father, mother and sister.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/18709478 Eliza Lang Edwards (1862 - 1947) - [[Find a Grave]] Memorial]</ref>

